        li
          a(href="#") Chemistry
        li
          a(href="#") Computer Science
        li
          a(href="#") Mathematics
        li
          a(href="#") Biomedical Engineering
    .two-column-child
      h3 Molecular, Cellular, & Developmental Biology
      .row-card
        +person("Stavroula Hatzios", "img/urm_faculty/hatzios.jpg", "Stavroula is an Assistant Professor of Molecular, Cellular and Developmental Biology in the Microbial Sciences Institute at Yale University. A native of Blacksburg, Virginia, she received her B.S. in chemistry from MIT and conducted her graduate work with Carolyn Bertozzi at UC Berkeley. After earning her Ph.D., Stavroula completed a research fellowship in Uganda before pursuing postdoctoral work with Matt Waldor at Brigham and Women’s Hospital/Harvard Medical School. Outside of the lab, she has been a longtime volunteer with science outreach organizations and has performed widely as an oboist. Her lab studies proteins that shape host-microbe interactions in gastrointestinal infections.", "mailto:stavroula.hatzios@yale.edu")
        +person("Maia Baskerville", "./img/urm_faculty/maiab.png", "Maia is a third-year graduate student in the Department of Microbial Pathogenesis at Yale. She graduated summa cum laude from Wells College with a B.A. in biochemistry and molecular biology. As an undergraduate, Maia pursued viral genomics research with Dr. Keith Perry at Cornell University and studied viral regulation of immune cell differentiation with Dr. Gary Chan at SUNY Upstate Medical University. As a current student in the lab of Stavroula Hatzios on Yale West Campus, she is investigating the redox effects of Helicobacter pylori on host cells. Maia is also a deputy editor for the Yale Journal of Biology and Medicine (YJBM), and volunteers with the United Way of Greater New Haven and strives to close the \"town-gown\" divide in New Haven through science and non-science outreach. Outside her scientific pursuits, she enjoys playing the piano, creating art, cooking, and maintaining her patterned sock collection.", "mailto:maia.baskerville@yale.edu" )
      h3 Ecology & Evolutionary Biology
      +person("Paul Turner", "img/urm_faculty/turner.jpg", "Paul Turner is the Rachel Carson Professor of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology at Yale University, and faculty member in Microbiology at Yale School of Medicine. He studies the evolutionary genetics of viruses, particularly bacteriophages that specifically infect bacterial pathogens, and RNA viruses that are vector-transmitted by mosquitoes. Dr. Turner received a Biology degree (1988) from University of Rochester, and Ph.D. (1995) in Zoology from Michigan State University. He did postdoctoral training at National Institutes of Health, University of Valencia in Spain, and University of Maryland-College Park, before joining Yale’s Ecology and Evolutionary Biology Department in 2001. His service to the profession includes Chair of the American Society for Microbiology (ASM) Division on Evolutionary and Genomic Microbiology, as well as membership on the National Science Foundation’s Biological Sciences Advisory Committee, ASM Committee on Minority Education, and multiple National Research Council advisory committees. Dr. Turner was elected Fellow of the National Academy of Sciences, Fellow of the American Academy of Arts & Sciences, Fellow of the American Academy of Microbiology, Councilor of the American Genetic Association, Chair of the Gordon Research Conference on Microbial Population Biology, and Chair of the CNRS Jacques Monod Conference on Viral Emergence. He chaired the Watkins Graduate Research Fellowship award committee for ASM, and received the E.E. Just Endowed Research Fellowship and William Townsend Porter Award from Marine Biological Laboratory, and fellowships from Woodrow Wilson Foundation, NSF, NIH and HHMI. Dr. Turner has served as Director of Graduate Studies and as Chair of the Ecology and Evolutionary Biology Department at Yale, as well as Yale’s Interim Dean of Science and Chair of the Biological Sciences Advisory and Tenure Promotion Committees.", "mailto:paul.turner@yale.edu")
      +person("Andrea Gloria-Soria", "img/urm_faculty/andrea_eeb.png", "Andrea Gloria-Soria was born in Mexico City and completed her undergraduate degree  in biology at the National University of Mexico.  She earned her Ph.D. at the University of Houston studying the ecological consequences of a behavioral polymorphism in the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans in the laboratory of Dr. Ricardo Azevedo.  She came to Yale University as a Gaylord Donnelley Environmental Postdoctoral Fellow from 2009-2011 to study genetic variation at a self-recognition locus in the cnidarian Hydractinia symbiolongicarpus.  She began working with mosquitos in Dr. Jeffrey Powell’s lab and transitioned to Associate Research Scientist in 2013.  In 2018, she joined The Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station as an Assistant Agricultural Scientist and she remains affiliated to Yale as a laboratory scientist.  Her current work involves the study of genetic variation to understand 1) the historical and modern distribution patterns of arthropod vectors, 2) the implications of genetic variation and vector/virus interactions in disease transmission.  The lab is a few blocks away from Science Hill and on the Blue-shuttle bus line.  She is happy to discuss research opportunities for undergraduate and graduate students.  You can find more information on her website: andreagloriasoria.wordpress.com.","mailto:andrea.gloria-soria@yale.edu")
      h3 Biomedical Engineering 
      +person("Anjelica Gonzalez", "img/urm_faculty/anjelicag.png", "Anjelica has a dedicated interest in training the next generation of scientists to think interdisciplinary and approach problems form a scientifically global perspective.  With a multi-disciplinary approach, the Gonzalez lab combines organic chemistry, molecular biology, mathematics, computational modeling and image analysis to develop and use biomedically engineering scaffolds to dissect the chemo-mechanics of immunological processes.  This work has special significance to an array of diseases and disorders, including atherosclerosis, arthritis, diabetes, cutaneous T-cell lymphoma, and sepsis.(Source: Faculty Page)", "mailto:anjelica.gonzalez@yale.edu")
      +person("Laura Morales", "img/urm_faculty/DSC03327.jpg", "Laura Morales is a Ph.D. student in the Biomedical Engineering Department at Yale University. She graduated summa cum laude from the University of Miami (UM) in 2018 with a B.S. in Biomedical Engineering. Her undergraduate research with Dr. Alice Tomei at the Diabetes Research Institute focused on characterizing polymeric biomaterials used in cell encapsulation and transplantation of islets of Langerhans in patients with advanced type 1 diabetes. During her time at UM, Laura was also an active member of the Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers (SHPE) chapter, where she served as treasurer during her senior year. In the Gonzalez Lab at Yale, Laura’s research focuses in understanding how neutrophils, the most abundant white blood cell in circulation, change as they cross the vascular wall and migrate to the site of inflammation. She utilizes biomaterials to engineer a composite microvasculature structure ex vivo, as well as several proteomics techniques. Outside of lab, Laura is co-president of the Graduate Society of Women Engineers at Yale, where she continues to work on stimulating URM to aspire and thrive as engineers and leaders in the community. In her spare time, she enjoys dancing ballet and salsa, cooking, and reading a good book. Laura is always happy to chat about anything and everything over a nice cup of Colombian coffee!", "mailto:laura.morales@yale.edu")
      +person("Amanda Alexander", "img/urm_faculty/amandaa.jpg", "Amanda Alexander is a fifth year PhD candidate in Biomedical Engineering in the lab of Kathryn Miller-Jensen.  Her research focus is systems immunology, where she is investigating regulatory mechanisms of cell-to-cell heterogeneity in the inflammatory response in macrophages.  She is particularly interested in how dysregulation of intercellular heterogeneity in inflammation may contribute to disease.  She is supported by an NSF Graduate Research Fellowship, and she also serves as a fellow in the Office for Graduate Student Development and Diversity (OGSDD).  She received her Bachelor’s degree in Mathematics from Spelman College in 2014.", "mailto:amanda.alexander@yale.edu")
      h3 Computer Science
      +person("Joan Feigenbaum", "img/urm_faculty/joanf.png", "Joan Feigenbaum is the Grace Murray Hopper Professor of Computer Science at Yale University. She received a BA in Mathematics from Harvard and a Ph.D. in Computer Science from Stanford. Between finishing her Ph.D. in 1986 and starting at Yale in 2000, she was with AT&T, where she participated broadly in the company's Information-Sciences research agenda, e.g., by creating a research group in Algorithms and Distributed Data, of which she was the manager in 1998-99. Professor Feigenbaum's research interests include security, privacy, anonymity, and accountability; Internet algorithmics; and computational complexity. While at Yale, she has been a principal in several high-profile activities, including the DHS-funded Pri-Fi Project, the DARPA-funded DISSENT project, and the NSF-funded PORTIA project. Her many service contributions to the research community include Program Chair of Crypto '91, Editor-in-Chief of the Journal of Cryptology (1997-2002), Program Co-Chair of the ACM Conference on Electronic Commerce (2004), Program Chair of the ACM Symposium on Theory of Computing (2013), Department Chair of the Yale Computer Science Department (July 2014 through June 2017), and General Chair of the inaugural ACM Symposium on Computer Science and Law (2019). Professor Feigenbaum is an Amazon Scholar, a Fellow of the ACM, a Fellow of the AAAS, a Member of the Connecticut Academy of Science and Engineering, and a Connecticut Technology Council Woman of Innovation. In 1998, she was an invited speaker at the International Congress of Mathematicians. (Source: Faculty Page)", "mailto:joan.feigenbaum@yale.edu")
      h3 Mechanical Engineering
      +person("Tony Odongo", "img/urm_faculty/tonyo.PNG", "Tony is a Postgraduate Associate at Yale. He works in the GrabLab as part of the Tech for Conservation team. He edited code to build a herbarium image classifier app that can distinguish between various reproductive states of plants. He also enjoys writing books as a hobby.", "mailto:tony.odongo@yale.edu")
      h3 Math
      +person("Taylor McAdam", "img/urm_faculty/taylorm.JPG", "Taylor McAdam is a Postdoctoral Fellow in the math department at Yale University.  She grew up in the city of Alameda in the San Francisco bay area.  She earned her B.S. in mathematics from Harvey Mudd College before starting a Ph.D. program in mathematics at the University of Texas at Austin.  Following the move of her advisor, Amir Mohammadi, she eventually transferred to the University of California San Diego, where she earned her Ph.D. in June of 2019.  She was awarded a National Science Foundation Postdoctoral Research Fellowship to work at Yale under the mentorship of Professor Hee Oh.  Her research focuses on dynamical systems on homogeneous spaces with applications to number theory.  She is also passionate about improving math education and promoting diversity and inclusion within the field of mathematics.  Outside of mathematics, she enjoys art, hiking and camping, craft beer, and snuggling with her cat, Igloo.", "mailto:taylor.mcadam@yale.edu")
      h3 Physics
      +person("Reina Maruyama", "img/urm_faculty/reinam.jpg", "Professor Reina Maruyama is an experimental particle/atomic/nuclear physicist, whose group runs experiments in direct detection of dark matter with terrestrial-based detectors for axions and WIMPs.  She was born in Japan and moved to the United States when she was twelve. She attended Columbia University for her undergraduate education and graduated with a B.S. in Applied Physics.  She received her Ph.D. in atomic physics from the University of Washington, advised by Norval Forston.  After obtaining her Ph.D., she became part of Stuart Freedman’s group at the University of California, Berkeley/Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory as a Chancellor’s Postdoctoral Fellow.  Her research journey continued at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, studying dark matter.  She has been a member of Yale faculty since 2013, and she received her tenure at Yale in 2016.  Professor Maruyama has authored over 200 publications and has received multiple awards, including Sloan Research Fellowship, Yale Public Voices Fellowship, and Woman Physicist of the Month from CSWP.  Outside of science, she enjoys downhill skiing, running, hiking, cooking, knitting, origami, and playing with her children and dog.", "mailto:reina.maruyama@yale.edu")

  